data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider allowed sync-over-async as an **opt-in** (via `CosmosOptionsExtension` / a warning suppression). In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), that opt-in is **removed entirely**. Synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally.

### Fix: switch to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods become `async` and use `await`
- Every LINQ terminal operator gets its `*Async` counterpart
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`

This is a **cascading change** — every caller up the stack must also become async (`async Task` all the way to the controller action). There is no workaround; the Cosmos SDK is fundamentally async-only, and EF Core 11 no longer hides that.
